"In the afternoon after five o'clock, no one dares to wander around the village," says Bardina.
It's a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was declared part of Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by public raising their hands in front of the occupying army.
The current movement protesting against Dutch rules quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region except for foreign journalists or civil rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is such a remote and ravaged city that you can reach after a ninety-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire, and then a five-hour stomach-clenching drive.
Public transport does not work in this place.
The town of 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, woolen roofs in shades of grey and rust.
Very few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and virtually no foreigners have visited this place.
Before the arrival of Christians, the locals worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
"We weren't used to wearing this dress," Bardina says, pointing to her colorful, hand-knitted turban, dark T-shirt and shiny skirt.
"Previously, we only carried leaves."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province - 28% of the population lives below the poverty line and its infant mortality and literacy rates are among the worst in Asia.
But at the same time, it is Indonesia's land of gold.
Grasberg, the world's largest and highest-grossing gold mine, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoeenix, USA, is located just 60 miles from Paniai — a rocky province about the size of New Jersey that is home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports logging worth an estimated $78 billion.
These riches, however, are a source of suffering for Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian military.
A 2005 investigation by the New York Times found that Freeport paid local military officials and units about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 for one officer.
Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore severely repressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
Mass murders in the tribal region of Papua during the 70s of the last century amounted to genocide, as stated by the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes the atrocities that took place last year as extrajudicial killings, torture — rape and electrocutions are particularly popular, according to another report — and the brutal repression of peaceful protesters.
"It's difficult to count the number of casualties because incidents happen every week," said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan sources were attracting colonists to Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants, 83% are Christian, but the demographics have changed with the influx of Muslim immigrants from Indonesia's islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, a mixture of vegetables and peanut sauce.
Local people are struggling to survive.
"Immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables at traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans," explains Abeth You, who was born in Paniai and moved to work in the provincial capital of Jayapura.
"The indigenous people of Papua — mama-mama (women) — have lost their jobs."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, promised to tackle inequality and rights violations during his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter secured and his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua and the local people feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi in the hope that he would answer our call for justice," You said.
The fact is that just two months after Jakowi's inauguration in October, Paniai experienced a major shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were singing Christmas songs around a campfire in the town of Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorbikes emerged from the gloom of the night.
Two of the surprised children told them they should turn on their lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by the rebuke and the tone it was spoken and later returned with four other soldiers, said local parish priest Yavedt Tebai.
Two of the drunken soldiers chased a group of children and beat them with the butts of their weapons, victims and witnesses said.
One of the soldiers then fired at a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby election commission building, and the next day things escalated.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and army headquarters to demand justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita dance - which runs in a circle and imitates the singing of birds - of the Papuan tribe of me Pago.
Several protesters began throwing stones at the buildings.
As tensions escalated, the soldiers were ordered over the radio: "If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are allowed to shoot," the official document, the contents of which were never published in local media, said, according to TIME.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Enarotali Kego Koto district, recognized the impending danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
But no one heeded his words.
"When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist," he told TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden home.
Kayame does not yet know who the shooter was, but he said the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
"There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting," he added.
One of the local residents, Alfius Youw, was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran to the body to make sure it was really him," Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME in a gloomy voice.
"I saw he was dead... I kissed him."
Papuan police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were merely "secure" the station, which was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten us with death," Papuan police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
Human Rights Watch said five protesters were killed and many were injured.
News of the murders rummaged through the Jakarta media the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an impassioned speech in Jayapura expressing his sympathy for the victims' families and promising to address the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it can never happen again," he said.
National Security Minister Wiranto announced in October 2016 that he would establish an out-of-court mechanism to resolve past acts of violence.
Almost immediately, however, excuses began to be heard.
"Most of the acts of violence happened a long time ago.
Some of them happened in the 90s of the last century and some at the beginning of the 21st century.
I mean, we are determined to punish these acts of violence, but it will not be an easy task," he said.
But in a June 5 interview with TIME weekly in Jakarta, Wiranto said he had no plans to implement any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said that "all cases will go to court."
Wiranto, who has been accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" on the basis of more than one thousand deaths during independent elections in East Timor in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua have been settled so far, including the incident in Paniai.
The families of the victims of the Paniai shooting greeted his claim with disbelief.
"I've been interviewed four times in the last three years, but so far I haven't gotten anything," Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
A few years later, he says, he still lives in fear.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid the army will arrest me or shoot me."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many Paniai residents who are afraid to talk about the incident.
He said he was beaten by members of the military after he helped bury four of the victims.
"After burying the bodies, the army started looking for me," he said.
And the shooting has not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in neighboring Deiyai.
The brawl, in which one person died and 17 others were injured, occurred between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to provide assistance in transporting the unconscious man to hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company's building.
According to police, villagers threw stones at the officers and were answered with warning gunfire.
However, locals claim that the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) opened fire on the crowd, killing one person.
"There was panic, we were afraid of retribution," Dominggu Badii, 29, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the arrival of the injured, told TIME.
"I haven't left the house for two days."
The Deiyai parliament demanded that the police officers involved be punished and the mobile brigade be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the Indonesian government's side.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of the indigenous people of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes who live in the central highlands.
Many have joined the Papua Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of rebels that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and kidnapping Indonesian police officers.
Some of the OPM leaders come from Paniai. These include Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks, the army has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of Paniai residents in recent years, all under the pretext of "ensuring national sovereignty."
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known among Papuans as a "tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty adds fuel to the fire.
The little rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
And bread is equally unattainable.
Locals grow their food: mainly sweet potatoes, fruit and leafy vegetables.
Women work in the fields; Each of them cultivates four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
Most of the harvest is for the needs of the family, the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten pieces of sweet potato cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Since Nabire Airport opened more air routes and new immigrants began to pour into the country, there has been an increase in economic inequality between native Papuans and immigrants.
Already few jobs are usually filled by more educated and wealthier immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the necessary capital and education to start a business.
"Young people are moving out of villages because of a lack of job opportunities and money," said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Thanks to isolation, the province of Papua is hidden from the world.
Strict rules for foreign journalists also contribute to this.
Earlier this year, two French journalists - Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp - were expelled from Papua for "lack of cooperation with the authorities", despite the fact that they had been given such rare permission to film.
Phelim Kine, deputy director of Human Rights Watch's Asia office, Jokowi campaigned on promises to lift strict rules for journalists and achieve transparency and development. However, this never happened.
"Foreign journalists working in the recalcitrant easternmost regions of Papua and West Papua are at great risk: non-recognition of visas and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of reports from foreign journalists means that international pressure on Indonesia over Papua is largely limited.
In March, six Pacific nations — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands — urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread acts of violence" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir shook off the accusations, telling reporters in Jakarta that: "Indonesia still has a democratic system and the media is free, so it is difficult to disguise evidence of human rights violations."
Local people are calling for the participation of foreign governments.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, headed by Human Rights Envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapurau on May 4, local people chanted "we want freedom," according to a source who also attended the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Another election is scheduled for 2019 in Indonesia, but Papuans say they will not vote for Jokowi.
"Jokowi is a well-intentioned person, but he is surrounded by people associated with the Paniai shooting," said Gobau, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai — in addition to living in constant fear of a marauding army — wallow in poverty, poor education, and a health system.
Gobai argues that the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote a "debt" that Jokowi must repay.
"They don't want money, they demand justice," he added.
Despite threats and intimidation by the families of the victims of the Panai shooting, they continue in a final symbolic act of defiance: they bury the bodies of the victims on the property opposite the police and army station.
Knowing that justice will never be done, at least he will not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed," Yacobus said with his head down.
"What can we do?"
