EPA chief Scott Pruitt on postponing planned emissions reduction guidelines by the Obama administration
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by fifteen states, its chairman, Scott Pruitt, retracted his earlier decision to delay implementation of the former Obama administration's plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt introduced changes as part of his plan. It responds more swiftly than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
But he made no mention of the legal challenge filed against his previous position in the Federal Court of Appeals.
This concerns the latest deadline, which has been set for 1 October, when countries should start complying with the 2015 regulation to reduce ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the deal for one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid "interference with local decisions or threatened economic growth."
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma's attorney general before President Donald Trump was appointed EPA chief, has long served as a staunch opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, D.C., Pruitt has repeatedly shifted or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil fuel industries.
Wednesday's abrupt reversal is the biggest legal setback for Pruitt's regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA executor had exceeded his authority in trying to delay the inclusion of the Obama administration's plan to require oil and gas companies to reduce methane spills.
In a statement issued Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed his version of ozone standards and strengthened the EPA's commitment to working with nations through comprehensive processes and meeting new standards within a given timeframe.
"Under the previous EPA administration, it often missed deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set plans," said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
"We don't believe in litigation regulation and we take meeting the deadline seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes with it."
However, the EPA statement said Pruitt could use "the delay option and all other legally available authorities" at some point to ensure that regulations "are based on sound policy and the most available information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader rewrite of ozone rules.
The White House budget approved last month seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measures still haven't passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed the coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group did not intend to allow legal pressure.
"The EPA's reversal — following our lawsuit — is an important victory for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution," Schneiderman said.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington, and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone is formed when common harmful substances emitted by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with solar radiation.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths every year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists welcome Pruitt's sudden change.
"It's worrying what pressure needs to be put into changing the mindset of those responsible and protecting the air we breathe," said Lori Ann Burda of the Center for Biological Diversity.
"We must continue to wrestle with the Trump administration's ideological crusade to aid polluters and special interests."
He doused the man with acid, yet he is not dangerous, according to the court.
