But Beijing is failing to do so.
The country's state media are talking about a plan to make tourism a driving force for economic transformation and modernization.
But arrivals rose by just 3.8 percent last year, and about 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
This is partly due to the fact that, despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, Christopher Balding, an economics professor at Peking University, assesses the situation in the world's most populous country in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for itself is China's visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free travel to China, while the others must obtain visas in advance.
Therefore, in the Chinese authorities in the US, the crowds are comparable to the celebration of the Chinese New Year.
A visa costs $140, but if you don't want to wait in line for hours, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions build significant economic barriers.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors to a given country by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while 1.8 million Americans visited Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China's gross domestic product and less than one percent of the total population.
China often exacerbates this problem itself, using tourism to further its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China restricted traffic to South Korea in the spring as part of a spat over South Korea's missile defense system, the South Koreans retaliated and avoided China.
In May, the number of visits fell 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan saw an increase of 85 percent.
All this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recently published report by the US Federal Reserve, up to $190 billion may have left China as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China earns about $35 billion annually from selling the currency to incoming tourists.
According to official balance of payments figures, China had a tourism deficit of $217 billion last year, equivalent to 44 percent of China's total surplus in trade in goods.
Thus, the small number of tourists is dealing a very painful blow to a country that is anxious to prevent capital flight.
However, the above-mentioned factors are only one manifestation of a more general reticence towards foreigners.
In many places in China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
As recently as 2013, fewer than a million foreigners lived in all of China.
Some individual cities in the United States have more.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads for immigration, has doubled.
A number of scientific papers show that immigrants tend to revive economic growth, entrepreneurship, and innovation.
However, you will practically not find them in China.
Resolving these problems will be politically challenging, but the obvious step is to simplify the visa apparatus.
Other Asian countries, notably India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and make visa procedures cheaper.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currency, it should be easier for them to get there.
