Moore's Ford Bridge massacre: activists commemorate racist lynching
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove past onlookers in Monroe, Georgia and strolled toward Moore's Ford Bridge.
But before the car, carrying four black passengers and a white driver, could reach the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its way.
The leader of the group—a middle-aged man in a striped suit—took a long drag from his cigarette and stared at the windshield of the car.
Inside, passengers trembled with fear.
"We want that n---and Roger!" the man shouted.
"Bring it to me!"
The silence is broken by the roar of a young black man who is pulled out of the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is merely a reconstruction of the events that took place on July 22.
But when one of the men throws a noose over "Roger's" neck, the audience sighs with excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have regularly returned to Moore's Ford Bridge to reconstruct that fateful night in 1946 when two black couples—Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murra Dorsey—were killed by members of the Ku Klux Klan.
No one has yet been tried for the murders.
"It's surprising that in all these years not a single person has been arrested – even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identities," said Tyrone Brooks, who is helping to organize the reconstruction.
"It's a stain on our history and a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of an event represents a dramatic challenge to action. Every year, he reminds the Monroe community that justice has not been done.
"We demand prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all," Brooks said.
"Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin."
On July 27, 1946, a forensic doctor covers one of the bodies of victims of the Moore's Ford lynching.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were believed to have participated in the lynching.
However, no one has yet been prosecuted.
Despite the suspects remaining free for decades, civil rights advocates say both reasons for the lynching — politics and sex — were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision gave black Georgians the right to participate in the elections scheduled for the summer for the first time.
It was during the summer election, according to the FBI, that black farmer Roger Malcom allegedly stabbed white landowner Barnett Hester during a scuffle — allegedly on behalf of his wife.
According to Brooks, it was rumored in the town that Hester had sex with Malcom's wife, Dorothy, and had brought her to another state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, then a prominent white landowner, posted $600 bail for Malcom.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
On their way back from prison, just before the entrance to Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
"As it turns out, Harrison planned and organized the murders," the FBI concluded.
"It is also clear that there was collusion between state and local law enforcement officers who not only participated in the lynching, but also disposed of evidence and concealed the identity of witnesses."
Brooks was more succinct.
"It was a massacre for the franchise," he said.
"The murders had a clear subtext to all local black residents: 'this is what you end up if you register and vote.'"
Cassandra Greene has been organizing the annual reconstruction of the Moore's Ford Bridge event for nearly a decade.
Her performance is figurative, engaging and concise. It shows a deep-rooted racism that many would like to consider extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction isn't easy, and it's even more difficult to look away, but Greene says it makes sense.
"Nobody wants to talk about lynching because we have to deal with the discomfort that lurks in all of us," Greene said.
"But there can't be a relationship between us unless you listen to what I've had to go through."
The main rehearsals of this year's reconstruction began in June, and on the first day some 30 actors—a dozen whites, the rest black—crowded into the room where Greene introduced them to a carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is an assistant director.
He played the leader of the Ku Klux Klan for many years, but says the role is exhausting.
"I feel bad about it because it contradicts who I am," Marbaugh said.
"I think it's very important to remember that part of history regularly because we never want to go back to that time."
Actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play the roles of Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, respectively, rehearse their roles.
The show begins with a fight - Malcom argues with Hester and accuses him of sleeping with his wife.
"Get out of my property n---e!"
Rascona can not.
There is a skirmish.
At that moment, everyone (at least every black actor) bursts out laughing.
Greene laughs the most.
"What happened?" he asks Rascona.
He is confused.
Was I too rude?
"No," Greene replies cheerfully.
"I just don't think whites said 'n--r' in that tone back then."
"Exactly," one of the black actors blurts out.
"You need to put more emphasis on R."
The energy in the room is suddenly better; Hostility will replace the feeling of rapprochement.
Everyone wants the performance to be authentic. If only to make enough for the four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
This time, Rascona emphasizes the correct pronouncing of the word N.
Now no one laughs.
The performance ends violently and quickly.
Roar, gunshots... and silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the bodies of the actors and sings Billie Holiday's mournful song "Strange Fruit".
With every word, there is a sense of sadness in the room.
Against the backdrop of all this, about a dozen onlookers wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
There are practically equal numbers of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple traveled all the way from Ithaca, New York, and many of the onlookers are from the vicinity.
Each endures the local humid climate for nearly eight hours, and Brooks leads them in a line to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up until now, the murders could have been viewed with hindsight, but now, standing in the same place where the lynching took place, the atmosphere is haunted.
With the last words of the song, Greene invites the crowd of onlookers to inspect the bodies.
Children kneel to the heads of the victims, watch the fake blood and motionless bodies, and whisper something in each other's ears.
"They're not dead," says the little boy.
A few minutes pass, and Greene thanks the audience. It's over.
The actors clean the rope and wipe away their tears.
Bradshaw embraces Marbaugh, the man in the suit who plays the leader of the Ku Klux Klan.
Nick Rascona hugs his two actor friends and cries in their arms; Eventually, emotions hit him.
"It's okay," one of the women whispers.
"We know you hate the role.
But you had a reason."
Later that day, the audience sits down with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple talk passionately about a performance with a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could hardly find the words to express her feelings about today's performance.
"It's difficult to listen to those ugly words and look at those ugly deeds... done by people who look like you and do it because they look like you," she said of the reconstruction.
"It makes me realize that lynching is still a hot topic," she added, "it's just called police skirmishes."
On the other side of the room, Tyrone Brooks sits in the courtroom. He enjoys his dinner while talking about civil rights.
According to his own words, he has already started planning the performance for the next year.
"The reconstruction of these events is inspiring because it describes the fear we had to experience – but it is also a moment for reflection," he said.
"If we don't learn from it, who knows... It could happen again.
People who do not know and study the history of their country are doomed to repeat it."
