Latest test results to determine the age of asylum applications in Sweden
The latest test results of asylum seekers in Sweden who were subjected to a new method assessing their age show that over 80 percent of people surveyed were over the age of 18, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency (RÃ¤ttsmedicinalverket) began conducting the new tests earlier this year.
The aim of the method is to assess applicants more accurately when evaluating asylum applications. The measure came after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted 6880 cases for investigation, and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2481 tests carried out between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
80 percent (2002) were assessed as over 18 years of age, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency concluded that the interviewee was "possibly over 18 years of age."
In a further 423 cases, it was decided that the interviewee was "possibly under 18 years of age".
Tests are only taken if the age of the interviewee is questionable.
According to Johan GÃ¶ransson from the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
"Compared to last month, the statistics are in business as usual and the numbers are very similar," he told The Local.
A higher number of applicants estimated to be over the age of 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers are lying about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases, "the interviewee was found to be 18 years of age or older."
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the respondent said he would be 18 years old this year.
The medical age-determination method, which includes X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, which are then reviewed by dentists and radiologists, has also received criticism.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus from the Karolinska Institute, which, among other things, deals with assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age at which the person went through puberty.
"I've had reason to think about this issue, and I don't think these types of age measurements are correct.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we can't determine age with precision, we shouldn't pretend otherwise," he told Metro newspaper.
Forensic medical agency Agency's GÃ¶ransson defended the decision, saying: "In general, the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the interviewee is just under 18 years of age, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all respondents."
