How football's financial rules will affect Neymar's move to Paris
Rules limiting the funding of European football clubs will not disrupt Neymar's record-breaking move from Barcelona in Spain to Paris-Saint Germain in France.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from the prestigious Champions League.
Financial Fair Play (FFP) rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 stipulate that PSG will have to prove that Neymar's transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid the equivalent of €222 million just to buy Neymar out of his contract, and Neymar will demand a salary of tens of millions of dollars a year.
The following are several financial terms of Neymar's move to France.
Given that PSG are funded by a wealthy Qatari family that made their fortune selling energy, they can afford to bring Neymar into an already stellar football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums on the purchase of players, but on the other hand they have to prove legal sources of income, which allows them to cover the overhead costs of football-related business activities.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his appointment as UEFA director in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that went into debt in search of new signings were ultimately cheating and risking bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to provide them.
In 2011, FFP rules shifted their focus from club debt to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model Roman Abramovich used with Chelsea in 2003 - buying a club with potential and spending exorbitant sums on players and building a global brand - was suddenly not so profitable.
Under the current three-year trial period, which ends in 2018, clubs can post a loss of up to €30 million.
And despite Platini having to leave his post in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Ceferin, is determined to defend a ban on overspending.
"The FFP rules are still in place and we are committed to strengthening them in the future," Andrea Traverso, who oversees FFP compliance, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid the amount for the purchase of Neymar in a lump sum, it can spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract for accounting purposes.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down to €44.4 million annually for five years.
The first wave of the highest FFP sanctions hit PSG in 2014, along with Manchester City, which is owned by Abu Dhabi Group.
PSG were fined €60 million ($82 million) – which was later reduced to €20 million – and ordered to reduce their Champions League squad to 21 players in 2014-2015, instead of 25.
UEFA is wary of teams that may try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their revenues through companies linked to club owners.
Thus, even if the Qatari company sponsors PSG, once the financing exceeds the value of the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the settlement of the amount.
UEFA took a similar measure in 2014 after deciding that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to PSG was too high.
Part of Neymar's income at PSG could be covered by the organising committee of the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar, according to some reports.
However, PSG and the 2022 World Cup officials in Qatar denied that Neymat should become a World Cup ambassador and that such a manoeuvre would have been easily detected by UEFA officials.
Previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
According to Tuesday's insiders, UEFA has not opened any investigation into Neymar's transfer to PSG.
The source of the report wished to remain anonymous as he was not authorized to comment on the PSG situation, The Associated Press reported.
The latest published financial statements show that PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of EUR 10 million and a turnover of EUR 542.4 million.
The accounts for the current financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expect the arrival of Neymar to be a huge opportunity for sponsors, merchandising and shirt sales.
The club expects to increase turnover by up to 30 percent from the signing of the contract.
Spanish league officials, apparently concerned about the departure of one of its biggest stars, sought to thwart Neymar's departure, arguing that PSG would break FFP rules.
"This is a clear case of 'financial doping' by the club and the state," la Liga president Javier Teba told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to PSG's ownership by a Qatari syndicate.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by the American sports mogul, shares La Liga's same stance on financing the club.
"It's the result of ownership that has fundamentally changed the football world over the last 15 years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"Once the state becomes the owner of the club, anything is possible.
Compliance with the rules of financial fair play is very difficult because the state may have different interests in the participation of such players in its club."
