Bank of England to keep interest rate at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to report that the interest rate will remain unchanged, following lackluster economic growth and weakening inflation, which has stifled speculation of a sharp rise.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain "in the background" as interest rates remain maintained - despite squeezing family budgets.
Politicians from the Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted six to two to keep the interest rate at 0.25%. The results of the vote to raise the interest rate supported lackluster economic growth supported by a weak increase.
In its annual inflation report, the bank forecast growth to 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018, and warned that cuts in family budgets would continue. The bank expects inflation to rise to 3% in the autumn.
At the same time, the bank indicated that over the next few years there should be growth due to inflation caused by Brexit and also said that rents from movable property in financial markets should rise more than expected.
Committee members also voted to withdraw part of the mammoth package designed to boost the economy, which was put into practice a year ago in response to Brexit.
As a result, the Term Finance Plan, which will offer cheap bank subsidies, is due to come into force next February, although the Bank of England has said it will now offer £15 billion less than the planned £115 billion.
Just before the decision, the bank said: "The MPC predicts that gross domestic product (GDP) will stagnate in the short term, with pressure on real household incomes and a burden on consumption."
On the subject of rates, the bank said it would take to "tighten the belts of monetary policy" to calm inflation, and to a "higher rate" than markets expect.
Markets are currently predicting a first increase in the third quarter of next year and a further increase in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that any increase would be "gradual" and "limited".
The bank lowered its growth forecast for this year and next compared to 1.9% and 1.7% forecast in May.
Projected growth of 1.8% in 2018 remained unchanged.
After the release of estimates, the pound fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to $1.31 and 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision to maintain the status quo came after disappointing growth buried hopes for further growth, with GDP stalling at 0.3% in the second quarter from 0.2% in the previous three months.
Growth will most likely remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it should increase slightly towards the end of the year, according to the bank.
The latest inflation report is little consolation for households hit by rising inflation and paltry wage increases. The bank said the situation would get worse before the increase.
The report goes on to say that monetary policy "cannot prevent" a decline in revenues in the coming years, but wages are expected to rise "significantly" towards the end of the three-year forecast.
The economy is also expected to grow due to strong demand for British goods due to the weak pound, offsetting a lower percentage of consumer spending.
The decision came a year after rates were cut to 0.025% last August in response to a shocking EU referendum vote that caused the pound to fall.
The bank estimates that it will take at least four years to fully unify prices and the economy.
Before the bank's decision on the latest rates, many had called for a rate hike along with rising inflation, which put increasing pressure on households. Three politicians demanded an increase to 0.5% in June.
Inflation fell back to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in June, despite the bank saying it had expected such a change and inflation was expected to rise again over the next month.
The bank said the excess relative to the 2% target was "entirely" due to the weak pound.
Andrew Montlake, Managing Director of Coreco Mortgage Brokers, said: "Given the recent fall in swap rates, it looks like competition in the mortgage market will only intensify as lenders start competing for contracts with a view to a good outlook towards the end of the year.
The market looks particularly good for those whose existing contracts and re-mortgages are coming to an end – there are fee-free options on offer, as well as low rates that are gaining popularity."
NHS to Prescribe Controversial HIV Drug to 10,000 Patients
Patients will have access to 'transformative' treatment to prevent HIV from September, following a Supreme Court decision on NHS funding.
England's National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to around 10,000 patients as part of a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to fund the probation after an appeals court upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year, saying the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP despite claims that local authorities should fund the drug.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was accepted by NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens as a 'significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. More clinics will join in October and by April 2018 there will be full implementation across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
Applying PrEP before sex means that there are enough specific medications in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will designate eligible participants who sign a consent to participate in the testing, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GPs in the UK can also apply at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The scheme will cost taxpayers £10m and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute medicines after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, targeting, using and implementing it at scale.
Simon Stevens added: "This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention efforts.
It is another milestone in more than thirty years of efforts to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health."
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust, said: "We are witnessing a defining moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients at risk, it will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
Starting in September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and does not require coaxing, which will improve the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to receive this declaration.'
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: 'The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; We must ensure that it is available to every patient.
We now have the trial drug PrEP and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV."
Shadow Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: "The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this medication may be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and together to end the spread of HIV in society."
High life: the mezzanine and clever design have turned this small apartment on Earls Court into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, swapped a large house in Knightsbridge for an apartment on Earls Cour in 2014.
Located on the first floor of the Queen Anne smart terrace, it is an example of modern design that makes the most of the available space.
"Before that, I lived with my ex-husband in a much larger house in Knightsbridge," Joanne said.
"I was looking for something more reasonable.
I stumbled upon this apartment in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I immediately fell in love with him and nodded to him the same day."
Since then, the 1000 square meter apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
A one-bedroom apartment with complicated layouts - you had to go through the kitchen to get to the bedroom - Joanne wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceiling.
"I wanted a high ceiling, big windows and lots of light.
Those were my demands," she said.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi of Notting Hill-based design and design studio Duck & Shed and used the nearly four-metre ceiling to create a home that was not only a project but also a place to live.
The ceiling was not so high that two gaps could fit above each other - the challenge for the architects was to create a mezzanine on which it would be possible to walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
"The steel structure is quite complicated," he explained.
"We had to arrange both spaces so that we could walk upright.
It was not only a matter of building a simple platform, but also of bending the steel structure so that it was at the right height above and below the ceiling."
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - and at the same time add to the drama.
On the mezzanine, old copper window frames in Retrouvius design overlook the beautiful living room.
Mirror furniture in gold color, silver lines and retro chandelier by Serge Mouille create a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor is equipped with mirrors on both sides and looks longer.
The mirror skirting board in the kitchen looks like a window to the next room.
At the entrance door there are storage areas equipped with mirrors for storing cutlery and glasses.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of significantly larger space, is the possibility to separate it from the kitchen when it is not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
However, what is unique about this solution are the folding doors.
"We had to sort out the technical side," says Erfan of the reinforced veneered door.
"The door is counterweighted to make it very easy to pull away."
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage space, Joanne gained an additional 16 square meters, a second room and a better overall layout of the apartment.
"For that matter, what you're selling is living space — or valuation of your property," Erfan said.
"Basically, a real estate agent calculates when entering an apartment, estimates its price based on the living area."
In this case, we managed to increase the living area while maintaining quality materials that give the space a luxurious look.
"The material is very important because you touch it and create an emotional bond with your home," Erfan added.
"You don't love the electricity in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but they will not win your heart."
As it turned out, high-quality design and increasing living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional work.
And just like Joanne, you may eventually decide to stay.
The United States is disconnecting.
The cultural and political gap between blue and red states is widening.
California has imposed a travel ban on its citizens traveling to Tennessee and seven other states.
The state of Tennessee retaliated and declared a retaliatory ban on its citizens traveling to California.
Of course, this is not a ban in the full sense of the word, US citizens can travel freely in all fifty states.
California has banned spending state money on its citizens' travel to eight other states: Alabama, South Dakota, Kansas, Kentucky, Mississippi, North Carolina, Tennessee and Texas.
Who will stop this madness?
California is strongly pro-LGBT and considers any expression of disagreement with LGBT lifestyles to be discrimination.
However, Tennessee has passed a conscientious objection law, according to which a psychotherapist who has a moral problem with therapy for LGBT patients is not obliged to provide it, but has an obligation to provide those patients with another therapist who does not.
Texas and other states have passed laws that require religious charities that give birth to children for adoption from their mothers are not required to give those children up for adoption to same-sex couples.
Because of these conscientious objection laws, California banned funding for its citizens' travel to eight states in the union.
In practice, this means that California professors are not allowed to have trips to scientific symposia in Texas, for example, reimbursed by their universities, because they are co-funded by the state of California.
Similarly, school sports teams cannot travel to tournaments or competitions in, say, Tennessee with financial support from their schools.
They must either obtain federal grants for travel, but it is absurd for the federal government to fund citizens' travel from state A to state B, or private sponsorship.
Tennessee has run out of patience and its House passed a bill with a resolution that it doesn't like California's policies of high taxes, high state spending, high deficits, and tolerance for illegal immigrants, but still doesn't impose a travel embargo on California because of it.
It imposes them in retaliation for California's travel embargo on Tennessee.
And the same will happen to any state of the Union that would impose a similar travel ban on another state for any reason.
At the same time, he called on the parliaments of all states to stop this madness.
These are the facts, now the commentary.
The situation is toxic.
First, all of this is constitutional, nothing is unconstitutional.
States have the right to pass conscientious objection laws, as well as to decide what their money will and may not go to.
Second, what's wrong with conscientious objection?
If a butcher has a religious problem selling pork, why can't he offer only beef, lamb, poultry and fish?
Why force him to sell pork under penalty when there are enough butchers offering pork?
In Colorado, a baker faces an anti-discrimination lawsuit and a hefty fine for refusing to bake a cake for a gay wedding.
But he also refuses to bake cakes for Halloween or containing alcohol.
Why punish him and leave him alone and order the cakes from hundreds of bakers of others?
Thirdly, the beauty of a federal system is that the constitutional rights of all citizens of the Federation are guaranteed, but individual States are free to adjust their internal, domestic policies with powers that are not federal to their liking, i.e., to the preferences of their inhabitants.
Then there is diversity, diversity, diversity.
California can be California and Texas can be Texas.
But California wants California to be California and Texas and seven other states to be California too!
Fourth, members of the LGBT community once rightly sought tolerance of their lifestyles.
Today, many members of this community follow the live-and-leave rule that all reasonable people should follow, but some activists seek extreme intolerance of others rather than tolerance of themselves and others.
According to them, no one should ever again express moral, religious or philosophical disapproval of the LGBT lifestyle, and if they do, they should be criminalized.
The mentality of these activists is totalitarian.
They are modern-day enemies of freedom.
Fifth, I don't know of a situation in American history where states have made such a fuss about political issues, except in one case.
Even in times of struggle for black civil rights, where North and West were on the side of integration and the South on the side of segregation, states did not impose sanctions on themselves.
The only case was the 50s of the 19th century, the political cause was slavery and the war of the North against the South was brewing.
Of course, this will not happen now, but the situation is still toxic.
The cultural and political gap between blue, democratic and red Republican states is widening, and the US is mentally disconnected.
