Heat in the Czech Republic.
Teachers shower children.
Public transport drivers get water and summer clothes.
In the kindergarten Na Chodovci in Prague 4, which is now attended by about 35 children, they go out only in the morning.
The nursery is after reconstruction and the planted trees do not yet provide much shade.
There is no swimming pool, but the teachers shower the children in the fog pit.
In the afternoon, children stay in classrooms where the blinds are drawn and the curtains are drawn.
They try to cool the air with an air purifier, because they do not have air conditioning.
It's also challenging for teachers and cooks.
"The temperature that is in the interior and exterior exceeds the hygienic limits for kindergartens, so we should not even have open operation during this period," said Miloslava Makovičková, the director of the kindergarten.
There is a glass corridor in the nursery, where the temperature is around 40 degrees, according to her.
We ventilate in the morning after 6 o'clock, close the windows and we have blinds on the south sides to protect ourselves.
"But it doesn't help much," she added.
Better conditions are in the forest kindergarten Na Hrázi in Hostivice, where children spend most of their time outdoors.
We have mature trees on the property, so we are under them.
"We have a beautiful walnut tree there, there is a table under it, and we do various things there," said Barbora Kompanová, the director of the kindergarten.
Teachers try to walk with children in the forest, where it is cooler.
Children wet caps and have various games with water on the program.
"We have a hand-held pressure sprayer that is used to spray flowers, and we use it to shower children," Kompan said.
Jitka Vilimovská, the director of the kindergarten on Novoborská Street in Prague's Prosek district, also said that the teachers try to keep the children in the shade and sprinkle them with water.
"We have a fairly mature garden, so they're under the trees," she said.
They go out in the morning and then after 3 p.m.
Every child must wear a head covering.
Teachers also remind children that they should drink.
They can choose lightly sweetened tea or diluted juice, for example, and there are drinking fountains with water in the garden.
They also have a vegetable salad to eat every day and fresh fruit and vegetables for snacks, sometimes brought to them by their parents.
"For example, today one mother brought about a ten-kilo watermelon for the children," Makovičková added.
Drivers receive water or a summer uniform.
The Prague Public Transport Company DPP provides them with water, ion drinks or summer uniforms on hot days.
The cabs of tram and bus drivers are in most cases air-conditioned, DPP spokeswoman Aneta Řehková said.
In addition to the cabins, some trams are also air-conditioned in the passenger area.
So far, the tram tracks have not been seriously damaged by the high temperatures.
Minor damage occurred in a loop in Hostivař.
