Trump's new chief of staff plans to curtail president's media diet
Before him, many have tried and always failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can really do it.
If so, he will be the first.
Politico reported that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of President Trump's information — including television news coverage — in hopes of keeping Trump afloat.
Here's part of reporter Josh Dawsey's report:
"When the new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly met with staff on his first day in his new role, he outlined a key problem with the Trump White House that he intends to fix: incorrect information that is getting into the president's hands.
Kelly told employees that they had to personally approve all the information — whether on paper or in a spoken word — because the president could make a better decision based on the right information."
Kelly's diagnosis actually makes sense, but many of his predecessors cut their teeth on Trump's control and media presentation.
Trump's relationship with the media dates back decades — and now that he's in the White House, his habit of watching the news is even stronger.
"If Trump as a candidate was upset by honest reporting, it was fitting to show him that he was being talked about in a positive light by a lot of other media outlets that were easier to convince," Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told POLITICO in February.
Politico's Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that "the key to keeping Trump's tweets in check — at least in the words of six former campaign organizers — is to ensure that Trump regularly watches media that praises him."
Okay.
But the idea that Trump's tendency to post his views on Twitter was ever "under control" is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaign organizers know something that others don't know — that Trump's tweets would be more outrageous if they weren't checked.
Tweets that Trump never sent will most likely never be known.
If his employees managed to keep him at bay at least a few times, then their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has been able to regularly prevent Trump from stirring up controversial topics.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, which consists of rival factions, people regularly try to strengthen their agenda by foisting materials — which may or may not be reliable — that support their worldview.
In May, Politico, which covered the issue from all sides, published a report on the propensity of advisers to present dubious information to the head of state.
This is an example of such information written by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Current and former Trump officials say the president often reacts very angrily to negative media reports, especially leak reports, and seeks to trace their origins.
That happened in late February, when someone slipped the president a copy of an article from GotNews.com — the website of provocateur Charles C. Johnson — that accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being a "source of many leaks" from the White House.
Regardless, Johnson was forever banished from Twitter for harassment; or that he has not substantiated his claim with any evidence; Or that he had published false allegations in the past and later retracted them.
Trump read the article and started asking questions about Walsh."
Goldmacher added that then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Secretary Rob Porter "tried to implement a system to manage and document the information that President Trump receives."
Would it work?
Now, three months later, Kelly is trying to pursue the same strategy.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump's impulsiveness is not going away, and his aides are still vying for power.
These immutable factors are sure to aggravate Kelly's mission.
