Michelle Carter convicted of texting Conrad Roy suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two years in prison for inciting her boyfriend to commit suicide via text messages and phone calls.
Twenty-year-old Michelle Carter will serve 15 months of her two-year sentence behind bars before spending five years on parole.
Carter was convicted in June of inadvertent manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who took his own life on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father told the court on Thursday: "The whole family is devastated.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was left at large pending a decision.
She faced up to 20 years in prison, but her lawyers argued that she and Roy suffered from mental illness.
Dressed in red pants and a cream blouse, Carter stood there as the verdict was announced, tears in her eyes, folded hands and eyes pointing to the ground.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the judge.
"She ended his life to relieve herself.
She couldn't accept her own responsibility," she said.
"She showed no remorse."
Carter's lawyer, however, said these were "unfortunate circumstances that she deeply regrets."
Judge Lawrence Moniz added that "her age or level of maturity or even mental disorder does not have a significant impact on her actions."
The prosecutor read a statement from Roy's mother, Lynn Roy: "Not a day goes by that I don't mourn the loss of my son.
I want him to be proud of me – I take care of his sisters and together we will endure the immense pain that we will carry with us forever," the statement read.
