Provence lavender threatened by climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in the southeastern French region, but is now threatened by climate change.
Lavender is declining due to the arid climate and harmful insects, causing consternation on the faces of researchers and farmers looking for solutions.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at the agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM in Provence, said: "Lavender cultivation in Provence is under threat because in the last few years this plant has been exposed to climate change, which brings with it less rainfall in spring and autumn.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
Cicadas and grasshoppers carrying micro-bacteria that thrive in arid climates are also to blame."
The stakes are high.
Lavender attracts tourists, and the oil produced from it is an important ingredient in perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: "Instead of long and beautiful flowers, smaller, undeveloped and often weak plants grow.
Of course, the amount of oil obtained from these lavenders is smaller."
A possible solution may be to distribute water more efficiently and slow the evaporation of water from the soil, but also to spray lavender with a protective mixture of clay and water and breed more species resistant to dry weather.
Murder of journalist highlights growing threats in Mexico
Riodoce staff meet regularly every Wednesday to discuss news about the unrest taking place in the Sinaloa region involving organized criminals, corrupt officials and the ongoing drug wars.
Today, however, under the onslaught of recent events, they gather mainly for their own safety.
They learn that it is important for them to change their habits.
Two veteran journalists talk about what would be safer: take their children with them to an office that was attacked with a grenade in 2009, or leave them at home.
Security experts wrote three simple words on the blackboard: adversaries, neutrals and allies.
They ask journalists to put names next to each word - no evidence is needed, just use imagination and premonition.
Drug traffickers, politicians, traffickers and journalists are suspected of taking money from the government or drug cartels - a catalogue of criminals whose job it is to cover up criminal conduct.
The violence does not cease and bodies pile up across the country; the number of journalists among them continues to increase: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, there are at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto came to power in December 2012; 589 journalists are under federal protection following attacks and threats; And seven have been killed in all seven states this year.
Among them is the co-founder of the periodical Riodioce, editor and inspiration for colleagues, Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and work as a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on the violence associated with drug trafficking.
His loss is felt, even if his presence is pervasive - a large photograph of Valdez with the inscription "Justice", pointing to the middle finger, hangs in the façade of the building; two journalists - Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez - over 30 years old, wear a T-shirt with a photo of Valdez with a smile on his face, glasses on his nose and a Panama cap.
The meeting takes place less than two months after his death; Journalists talk about mutual traumas, nightmares, insomnia and paranoia.
Despite the fact that a special federal prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 to handle journalists' cases, it has so far prosecuted two suspects, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Most of the thousands of murders that occur each year are linked to drug trafficking and organized crime. Journalists' killers are very rarely brought to justice.
Riodoca journalists insist on reporting on the violence taking place in Sinaloa; Even though they are devastated by grief and the territory is currently very treacherous.
Without information about the killers and no prospect of justice, a meeting about security is pointless, Ibarra says.
"It's foolish to waste time on meetings like this," he adds.
"If we don't get more information, no one can be trusted."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the headquarters of Riodoca in Culiacán, the capital of Sinaloa.
He managed to drive several blocks when his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men who pulled him out of the car and killed him with 12 shots, apparently because of the title of the article - which translates as The Twelfth River.
The gunmen then got into his car and crashed him not far from the scene.
Valdez died at the age of 50.
He left behind a wife and two adult children.
Rumors seem to spread quickly in Culiacan.
In Valdez's case, however, there is a suspicious silence.
Since Guzman's arrest last year and his extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa has become one of the country's bloodiest battlegrounds as rival factions try to fill the void.
Several people are killed every day on the streets of Sinaloi, and the cemetery is full of ornate two-story mausoleums for drug kings, many larger than houses.
Forget for a moment that the word "ceasefire" means that one drug cartel controls a coastal state with precious ports and important routes through which drugs travel to the United States.
Despite this, as well as the fact that Valdez was intimately aware of the risks of his job, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, the co-founder and CEO of Riodoce, still blames himself for not protecting his friend.
He believes two misconduct contributed to his death.
The first was the February edition of an interview with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival drug cartels that waged war with the sons of Joaquín Guzmán.
Reconciliation could have angered the sons; The suspected gang members bought up all copies of the newspaper the moment it landed on the shelves.
The second mistake was not to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of another newspaper in which the same story was printed.
Valdez has become a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his death is seen as an important milestone in Mexican criminals' fight against journalists.
He managed to survive for so long, and all his friends and colleagues believed that it would never change.
He was virtually a veteran at Noroeste when he decided to sell his $50 stock in 2003 and form Riodoca with five colleagues.
In Sinaloe, "it was impossible to run journalism without mentioning the drug trade," Bojorquez said.
Over time, Riodoce gained a reputation for brave and truthful reporting; The newspaper began to thrive.
