The newspaper's director, Bojorquez, is visiting Washington today to seek international support and justice for Valdez's death.
At a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez's murder, Ramirez accused authorities of spying on journalists and murdering them for telling the truth.
In the meantime, she has asked to be transferred to another department for fear that her anger could jeopardize her impartiality.
Valdez has repeatedly said Mexican journalists are "surrounded by" organized crime, corrupt officials and an indifferent public.
In his latest book, "Narco-journalism," he wrote that journalists die not only at the hands of drug cartels, but also at the behest of politicians and security forces who collaborate with organized crime.
Media surveillance group Articulo 19 blamed more than half of all attacks on journalists, police officers and public officials.
"You die in Mexico because they want to silence you," Ramirez added.
Murders obviously work.
No one will forget the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macías six years ago near the northern border of Tamaulipas.
Her body was found along with a note allegedly signed by the Zetas cartel: "This is how I ended up because of my messages."
Next to the severed head lay a keyboard and headphones.
Some branches have decided to shut down, such as the newspaper El Norte, based on the northern border of Chihuahua state, in response to the murder of correspondent Miroslava Breach in March.
Others still continue, just as El Manana of Nuevo Laredo did after the killing of its director in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed drug cartels with a front-page article titled "What do you want from us?"
Some journalists have fled their homes or even across the border.
It is a difficult decision.
