Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however frightening.
Researchers have now revealed the findings of the first findings of an amazing rhinoceros-sized creature whose perfectly preserved remains — which experts have dubbed the 'Mona Lisa of dinosaurs' — were found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved at such a high rate that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of its scaly skin and stated that the dinosaur had a 'troubled past'.
An article in the journal Current Biology called it 'the best preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur species in the world'.
The fossil is a new species of the family Nodosauridae. The dinosaur lived in the Cretaceous Period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
Its perfectly preserved condition shocked researchers, who described it as 'truly remarkable'.
The armored herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind to date, according to National Geographic.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He came across what looked like a foreign object and decided to examine it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Researchers spent the next six years working to excavate the animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1100 kg.
After the work is completed, the dinosaur is ready for detection.
'You just have to squint a little and you'll believe he's asleep,' said lead author Caleb Brown and naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
'It will certainly go down in history as one of the most beautiful and surviving species of dinosaur - the Mona Lisa dinosaurs.'
By studying its skin, the researchers found that this herbivore — despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank — was most likely to face a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a camouflage system used by many animals today.
Experts say this allowed him to blend in better with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The camouflage system suggests that it was the favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
News of a 110-million-year-old dinosaur of the Nodosauridae family first appeared in newspapers in May. It is currently available for inspection at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum engineer Mark Mitchell, who and his team spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists document the patterns and shape of scales and armor throughout the body.
They revealed a camouflage method commonly used by today's animals in defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this camouflage effect is common in nature, the researchers' findings are surprising because Borealopelta's size far exceeds today's animals using the same technique.
It is possible, therefore, that the dinosaur was so numerous predators that evolution preferred camouflage to confrontation in survival.
Many present-day camouflaged animals—such as deer, zebra, and armadillo—are much smaller and more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus must have literally fought for its survival.
"The predation of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur illustrates the danger posed by predators during the Cretaceous period," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur skin was likely reddish-brown in color.
Researchers continue to study the animal and search for more information about its life, including preserved stomach contents, to trace its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell into the river after death and was carried to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
The Alberta area at that time had the same climate as in present-day Florida, and the rivers and oceans stretched much farther inland than they do today.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin and at the same time it is preserved in three dimensions so that you can see its original size," Brown said.
'For these reasons, the animal looks practically the same as it did in the Cretaceous era.
You do not need to use your imagination to reconstruct it; Just squint a little and it looks like he's just sleeping.'
In the Cretaceous period, huge theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs that moved on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the king of all dinosaurs, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been the favorite prey of its equally fearsome ancestors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, an 11.5-meter-long monster weighing over 6 tons.
The researchers, whose latest findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelt's body was washed up into the sea after being mummified in mud.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including its skin and armor, and is complete from the snout to the hip.
The animal averaged 5 meters in length and weighed up to 1300 kg.
Two 50 cm spines protruded from his shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivore roamed what is now Canada until it ended up in a river that washed it into the sea.
His underwater tomb preserved the body in perfect condition.
The fossil remains of this species are also preserved to the extent that armored plates around the skull still cover the remains of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, 'finding such a surviving individual can be compared to winning a lottery.
The longer I watch it, the more shocking I find the find.
