I can easily count the scales on his foot.'
How did one activist find out the answer to the question: 'Whose Streets?'
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shook all over her body.
The day after arriving in New York, the St. Louis native sat on a bed in her Airbnb room and scrolled through Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across a post by a high school student.
"Police have just shot dead an 18-year-old youth whose body is still lying in the street," it said.
She was surprised that no one else had written her the post, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user @TheePharoah constantly retweeted her wall posts.
The St. Louis rapper tweeted about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old who was shot and killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying motionless on the street, from where he had not been taken away after four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put her phone down to return to it in the evening, watching tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
She watched photos of police tapes and people screaming. One of the men claimed to be the victim's father and held a sign that read, "Ferguson police killed my unarmed son!"
She watched the live news - one of the policemen stood in front of a group of protesters, holding a leash and a dog barking at the other end.
In another video, another police officer held a gun she said pointed at the crowd and yelled, "I'm going to kill you all... animals."
"That's not normal," Ferrell told herself.
"This is not the kind of murder we've become accustomed to and can call normal.
I felt goosebumps all over my body.
"I was angry and crying."
She immediately booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11:00 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided to head to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is told in a new documentary, "Whose Streets?" that will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and resistance, strength and resilience, told from the perspective of people living in a community who take to the streets and demand answers.
On the way to Ferguson, Ferrell initiated a dialogue with her daughter — dressed in a floral jersey and the same floral headband — about a topic they had discussed many times before — "the experience with black people."
"Remember how I taught you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?" she recalls.
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old and that's not right."
"There was no way I wouldn't take her with me," Ferrell said later.
"Today's events are the culmination of... that happened in the past.
She had to know it and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organization, but she also needed to know the difference between the different layers of experience with blacks and what we had to do to liberate ourselves.
Although I am able to provide her with conditions in which she does not experience racism firsthand, she is no different from another black child – a woman.
I feel that if I protected her from this experience, I would only hurt her."
Upon arrival in Ferguson, the first stop was South Florissant Road, opposite the Police Department, which became a base for activists who awaited Officer Darren Wilson's words about his possible involvement in the incident.
There, Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who was preparing food for others.
Together they prepared food in bags and helped distribute it to the Protestants.
In Ferrell's eyes, a new type of activism was slowly emerging.
"My activism was turned upside down after Aug. 9," Ferrell said, adding that while attending a college at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she said. Louis was president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. and pushed for health care and food in black communities.
"I had no experience with organization.
It was natural."
A few weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met the documentary's later co-director, Sabaah Folayan.
Folayan said he and her cameraman, Lucas Alvarado-Farrar, wanted to "just document" the events.
But Ferrell wondered, "Are you working on a documentary, or are you trying to find a story that can be used?"
This type of skepticism permeated the community through many people, often white, who wanted to capitalize on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in a non-daunted interview, "We've heard that the voices of people who are born and raised in Ferguson are very often neglected, and we wanted to change that."
Folayan has already partnered with co-director Damon Davis, an acclaimed local artist who works on the subject of death row inmates.
His participation in the project also involved Ferrell and six other locals who were tracked by the "Whose Streets?" team in the years following Brown's assassination.
"No one is speaking for us in this document, but it's our testimony," Davis said.
"That was important to me — how these people will be represented — because that's how I'm going to be represented."
While the documentary's goal wasn't to focus on Ferrell's experiences — in an effort to portray that the movement "isn't about a savior leader, but about bringing the community together," Folayan said — she turned out to be the most open to participating in filming.
"Whose Streets?" describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell's life, such as how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said with a smile on her face as she thought of the first time she saw the final version of the documentary.
"But I understood that in order to do this job and humanize black people, I had to open up."
Ferrell's story also highlights the role of the eccentric black woman in the broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three founders — who created a social media #BlackLivesMatter campaign in response to the killing of teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 — call themselves weirdos.
"Black eccentric women in leadership positions are ultimately committed to preserving the movement," Ferrell said, "because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women have to endure the weight of these events."
Folayan agrees, adding that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of eccentric black women."
She insists, however, that "this is not just an affirmative affirmative issue" and Ferrell is not the protagonist of the documentary because of her views.
"She was the driving force and the source of energy," she said.
"That she found herself on the front lines is no coincidence, because life at these intersections in the skin of a black weirdo woman is dangerous.
You can feel the rush of energy in front of the screen."
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, the TV cameras have vacated their positions, but the heavy racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is serving a two-and-a-half-year suspended sentence for blocking the highway during demonstrations.
She described the socio-political atmosphere in the area she calls home "disorder."
Yet she continues the commitment she has made since taking to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
The only thing we have to lose is our chains."
