A Becoming Resemblance: the artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of New York's Fridman Gallery are several faces of different skin tones - white, black and dark - hanging from the ceiling on wires. Each of them seemed to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for illegally publishing classified cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2nd, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he left the US presidency.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with that genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a poignant, if not intellectual, commentary on the docility of DNA—as well as the many ways DNA can be interpreted—and the inherent determinism of those interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken from a young age about considering herself a woman. She was convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including violation of six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All her photographs were withheld by prison staff. Only one lower-quality black-and-white photograph was leaked, showing Manning, visibly alarmed, sitting in the driver's seat in the platinum blond wig with which she is now associated.
In 2015, positive responses to Dewey-Hagborg's 2012 project Stranger Visions were still reverberating.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of possible images of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They were interviewing Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to supplement the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, visits and photography were not allowed, so they contacted Chelsea to ask if they would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, a few days after the comic was published, President Obama asked for Manning's release, a welcome change after several unbearable years in a military prison in Kansas.
Interestingly, the exhibition comes at a time when Donald Trump is waging war on government insiders and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to stoke resentment in areas he is supposed to support with his tweets.
In response to a question about this strange timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that "everything happens for a reason."
Under the artist's statement on one of the gallery walls, Manning, with her huge signature (the letter "i" in her surname is dotted with a heart), calls for an end to "automatic factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality, and culture."
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of the letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific vocabulary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope people take away that our genome doesn't care who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way," Dewey-Hagborg said. You can also see her 2007 work Spurious Memories on the theme of video.
"DNA tells a lot of different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last copy of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is a single page from the above-mentioned graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging from the United States Disiplinary Barracks with a megaphone in her hand.
"As soon as they prevent you from speaking, they win," it reads.
"Never be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"It gives me goosebumps when I think about it."
Manning has yet to visit the exhibition in person — as predicted in the comic book — but when she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room with her masks, her own genomic effigies, lined up like a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the almost 160 cm tall statue of Maningová, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
"In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted them to exude the feeling of a crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates them."
Northwest University professor and Oxford University employee wanted for murder
A nationwide manhunt is underway for a Northwestern University professor and Oxford University employee who are being prosecuted on suspicion of murdering a man who was found stabbed to death in a luxury Chicago apartment, police said.
On Monday, arrest warrants were issued for first-degree murder for a man named Wyndham Lathem, 42, and Andrew Warren, 56, for their alleged complicity in the death of Trenton H. James Cornell-Duranleau, according to a Cook County court file.
The document says Cornell-Duranleau, 26, died from multiple stab wounds.
Chicago police said the body was found on July 27.
Police officers were alerted to this fact by telephone. Upon arrival at the Grand Plaza Apartments, they found the victim in one of the apartments with several lacerations.
Cornell-Duranleau was pronounced dead at the scene, and detectives are investigating the case as a homicide. Meanwhile, police are searching for the two suspects, authorities said.
Lathem has served as an associate professor of microbiology and immunology at Northwestern University since 2007.
Alan K. Cubbage, the university's vice president of public relations, said in an email statement that Lathem is now on administrative leave and has been banned from the university's campus.
"The matter is now being investigated by the relevant authorities and Northwest University is cooperating fully with them," Cubbage said.
Warren is an executive financial administrator at the University of Oxford.
A spokesman for the university and Somerville College said in an emailed statement: "We have been contacted by British police and are ready to assist US police as well."
The statement also said Warren's colleagues were shocked by the fact and wanted him to turn himself in to police.
Anthony Guglielmi, head of public relations for the Chicago Police Department, said he was urging suspects to surrender to appropriate authorities.
"Police have information about their whereabouts and efforts to track down the suspects are intensifying," Guglielmi said.
Guglielmi added that local, regional and national authorities are assisting police in the search for the suspects.
According to Guglielmi, police received a call from the manager of the Grand Plaza building, who was alerted to the events that were supposed to have occurred in apartment 1008.
Police described the scene as very violent.
Guglielmi said it was unclear if the incident occurred on July 27.
He added that Lathem and Warren were caught on security cameras.
"We believe Professor Latham knew his victim," Guglielmi said.
Grand Plaza management issued a statement to all residents: "Police are now working to compile a timeline and profile of the victim and are investigating various motives, including domestic violence."
"We will finalize the WADA plan in the near future" - Deputy Prime Minister of Russia Mutko
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said it would not be long before the remaining criteria of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) and the re-establishment of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) would be implemented.
"At present, part of the criteria of the new plan has already been finalised and RUSADA has already obtained the right to plan and test in cooperation with the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
With this in mind, WADA's plan has been updated," Mutko said Thursday.
The Vice Chairman commented on the second part of WADA's plan to comply with the Code – which describes the renewal criteria for RUSADA – which was recently posted on the organisation's website.
According to Mutko, the code contains nothing to worry Russia.
"Everything has been announced and everything will also be implemented.
The results will be available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future," he added.
One of these criteria, however, calls for the public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation by Richard McLaren into the government's alleged sponsorship of doping of Russian athletes.
Mutko said: "We are conducting an investigation because our anti-doping system has clearly failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there were no state programs in our country, so we can't admit to something that never existed."
Mutko's words were confirmed by Vitaly Smirnov, director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russia's RSport, Smirnov acknowledged the problems of Russian anti-doping officials, but added: "We have stated on many occasions that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report completely without reservations," Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected RUSADA of imposing doping controls within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
However, the organisation allowed planning and unification of testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) in June this year.
After visiting the organization's Moscow headquarters in July, WADA Director General Olivier Niggli said RUSADA was "on the right track" to renew.
Police have charged three people, one of whom is a juvenile.
Police have charged three men with setting fire to a rare wooden church in Třinec-Guty in the Frýdek-Místek region on Wednesday.
One of the accused is a juvenile, all three are of Czech nationality.
They face up to 15 years in prison for the crime of public endangerment.
Moravian-Silesian Police Director Tomáš Kužel told journalists today.
According to him, it was a deliberate crime.
"It's a very recent issue and the police are currently working on a motive," Kužel said.
He said police would discuss the possible remand of the accused.
Further information cannot be disclosed, according to the director.
"I can't say more yet, because the criminal police and investigation service and the public prosecutor who supervises the matter are really working on the matter," Kužel said.
The wooden church of Corpus Christi in Guty dates back to the 16th century.
It was a valuable monument with many original furnishings and paintings from the first half of the 16th century.
According to preliminary estimates, the material damage will amount to tens of millions of crowns, but the historical loss is incalculable.
Soon after the fire, the restoration of the church began to be considered.
Most of the costs should be covered by insurance, the Ministry of Culture and the city are ready to share other costs, a public collection is also being prepared and a contribution from the owner of the monument, i.e. the local parish, is expected.
A similar wooden church of St. Catherine from the 16th century in Ostrava-Hrabová was also destroyed by fire fifteen years ago.
It was caused by a defect in the wiring.
In its place, an exact copy was made.
The state counts on citizens to defend the state.
It will support their training.
Financial support for associations usable in the defence of the state, voluntary shooting training or a team of training trainers is envisaged by the factual intention of the Act on the Readiness of Citizens for the Defence of the State.
The Ministry of Defence, which was given the task of processing it by the government, hopes that it will succeed in increasing the physical fitness of Czechs and their abilities, which could then be used by the state in crisis situations.
This follows from the proposal prepared by the Ministry.
If the law is adopted in the future, the state would spend hundreds of millions of crowns on military support.
According to its authors, the basic objective of the proposal is to create an effective system that would help increase the readiness of the population of the Czech Republic to defend the state, outside the performance of military duty and on a voluntary basis.
For example, the state would support associations of radio amateurs, shooters or cynologists with financial or material and would make it possible to increase the abilities of their members.
In return, it would obtain data on people who are willing to come to the aid of the country in times of crisis if necessary, and on their capabilities or material equipment.
Accredited instructors could also be available to help associations and other interested parties with training or education.
It is also planned to organize discussions with war veterans or people who behaved heroically.
One of the possible options assumes that a new office would be created to be in charge of the administration and coordination of the project.
The authors of the proposal emphasize that people's participation should be voluntary and the state would use their abilities only after a state of emergency has been declared.
"The whole concept must respect the gradual blurring of previously obvious boundaries between individual types of threats," the plan states, referring to the dangers of so-called hybrid threats.
Ministry officials noted that it is therefore necessary to focus on supporting the widest possible set of capabilities, not just military ones.
"The basic objective of the plan is to create a very broad base that will enable every citizen to respond competently to situations threatening the sovereignty of the state or the lives, health and property of persons, to protect themselves or contribute to the protection of others, and not to complicate the performance of tasks by the Armed Forces of the Czech Republic by improper behavior," the plan states.
The adoption of the law would bring considerable financial demands.
According to the ministry, their amount will depend on the chosen option.
For example, the Office anticipates financial support for projects to prepare citizens for the defence of the state up to CZK 100 million.
If an administrative and coordination centre were established, its operation could cost around CZK 60 million a year.
Other money would go to salaries or to build an information system.
The proposal also foresees that the remit of regional military headquarters would have to be expanded, which would employ a total of 42 additional soldiers.
Representatives of the ministry have previously said that the law should also help resolve the disagreement of some Czech politicians with the introduction of the European Union directive on the possession of weapons.
Its adoption would allow shooters who will be part of the system to keep some of the weapons prohibited by the directive.
Startups that help your company stay the next Uber
Amy Erretta wanted to measure the satisfaction of employees at her e-commerce startup, but couldn't find a matching survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, unhelpful, or even deceptive.
And despite promising the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity," said Errett, owner of San Francisco-based hair care e-commerce company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
So she asked for outside help.
New HR startups are constantly appearing on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intention of measuring employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographics, offer complete employee anonymity and a complaints hotline, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass supervisors and contact CEOs directly.
"There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that Glint has given her a greater awareness of what her employees are thinking and feeling in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and specific team polls, Glint offers a company heat map and a quick overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low-rated managers – allowing the user to work on remediation.
Companies are beginning to realize the need to be mindful of the culture of the work environment — in case they become the next Uber — which is mired in scandals after a former employee posted on his blog describing the company's environment and the harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to Let's Talk Payments, a website dedicated to technical and financial advancements, the value of the global control, regulation, and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Convercent, a Denver, Colorado-based startup that helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small surge in interest and activity earlier this year, just before the Uber scandals.
Convercent's nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, it has also taken Uber under its wing.
Similar to Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable "lightning" surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the CEO is involved, complaints are sent directly to the Board of Directors.
"The Court of Public Opinion has empowered regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of startup Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behavior — and regulators fail to step in — it could face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, employee exhaustion or lawsuits, Quinlan added.
Employing more than 25,000 people across 500 locations, Ruby Tuesday has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employee awareness of corporate policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate management.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to find a phone number or e-mail to the company's management, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful resolution.
It was often a discouraging and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, general counsel for Ruby Tuesday, who said there had previously been no reliable way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, it ensures that problems are quickly detected and resolved that never before reached office managers, miles away from actually resolving complaints – such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
"It's closer to a holistic, holistic view of the employee experience," said Vitrano, who manages the risk management group at Ruby Tuesday.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from lawsuits from employees."
Companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed following the collapse of Enron over the abuse of employees' ethical rights, Quinlan said.
But it wasn't until "social media took a spot" that companies began to realize that they couldn't simply hide their skeletons in a closet online.
"Before people started using technology to track ethics, they relied on faith," Quinlan added.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It's a business model and an opportunity endorsed by bold equity investors who have backed both startups.
Convercent raised a total of $10 million from Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital as part of its February campaign, eventually taking home $47 million in capital.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and raised $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the reciprocal nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research clearly confirms that today's employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high salaries and interesting projects.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued, and that they dedicate their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
"When people are happy in their jobs, feel that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they are committed to the company's success," said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money if a company is doing well, and a company prospers if its employees are happy.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure employee engagement and commitment to the company, it is not surprising that there are many investors who support this effort.
According to experts on work culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is pointless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The reality is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, big changes can happen.
And if change does not happen quickly - in the worst case not at all - it can cause disappointment and disinterest of employees.
"Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations," said Russell Raath, chief advisory officer at Kotter International, who has witnessed many companies relying too heavily on data alone.
"Because as soon as you don't get things done, employees start asking, 'Did they even hear me?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, then why should I care?'" "
Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, can solve the problem in one day thanks to Glint, Herretto said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision-making and the quality of communication, Erretta was able to reorganize several teams within the company and begin communications training to successfully resolve the issue.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important insight into its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the long run in an industry known for frequent layoffs.
"If you don't strive to create a transparent work environment, employees won't trust you," Vitrano added.
"And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt."
Thursday became the hottest day.
With 38.3 degrees recorded in Strážnice in the Hodonín region, Thursday is the hottest day of the year in the Czech Republic so far.
It surpassed Tuesday, which was originally the hottest day of the year at 37.3 degrees.
The staff of the Czech Hydrometeorological Institute informed about it.
Compared to Tuesday on Thursday, however, there were not many temperature records.
The heat hit mainly Moravia, Bohemia was mostly cloudy.
On Tuesday, records were broken or equalled at 35 of the 145 weather stations measuring more than 30 years.
On Thursday, only nine long-term measuring stations recorded a record.
For example, in Strážnice, today's temperature was the same as the previous record from 2013.
In Lednice in the Břeclav region, today's 37.4 degrees exceeded the original maximum by four-tenths of a degree, and in Pohořelice in the Brno region, the current 37.1 degrees exceeded the record by three tenths.
Both records, as well as at Strážnice, came from 2013.
High temperatures appeared today mainly in the south and east of Moravia.
After Strážnice, the hottest was in Dyjákovice in the Znojmo region and Brod nad Dyjí in the Břeclav region, where the mercury climbed to 37.8 degrees, but did not break the record.
On the other hand, in western and northwestern Bohemia, for example, today's highest temperatures were only around 22 degrees Celsius, according to the CHMI website.
"Temperatures there only started to rise later this afternoon," meteorologists said.
According to CHMI, the current heat in the Czech Republic will gradually subside and more significant rains could come on Sunday.
In most places in Moravia, however, high temperatures will remain on Friday and in the south-east of Moravia on Saturday.
