Making a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
The small Scotney Castle recently played the main role in the music video of the band Squeeze and Margaret Thatcher also found refuge there during the 70s and 80s of the last century.
But from his cozy spot by the River Bewl in Kent, UK, Scotney witnessed 700 years of turbulent history that inspired the curly-haired Jamie Rhodes of Yorkshire - known for his penchant for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"Looking at the writing of a man who is 300 years after death fascinates me," says Rhodes with a straight face.
"When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of the families who lived at Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, this is not Rhodes' first book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by the British Library documents – a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 70s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like going back in time.
How I love archives!"
For someone who is so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to stay in the castle for almost four months is almost like a dream. ("To tell you the truth, I extended my stay a bit.")
Rhodes spent his time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, browsing the archives and studying the many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on the wall and bottles that had been dumped in a moat for centuries.
He walked around the property and explored the ruins of the old castle, talking with gamekeepers, gardeners and occasionally with artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
At night, he "drank whiskey and wrote."
Scotney's intimate history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained access to the documents in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, employees were just beginning to break into the archives, which Rhodes described as "aristocrats of many centuries throwing up their hands saying, 'Take it to the attic.'"
Diaries, letters from the days of the British Empire, maps showing estates: "You may think that a land dispute is boring," said Rhodes, "but I have come across one case where two families were fighting over a birch tree.
Stop the people!"
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English Rebellion of 1381.
"I found a record of a revolt in the castle in 1380 called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book," Rhodes said.
"The English insurrection actually began in this area, and it occurred to me that the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're related after all."
Other stories are closely tied to the history of the castle, such as The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by Darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who supposedly staged his own funeral by filling the coffin with stones (which wasn't discovered until several years later after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes' favorite family is the Darrells: "I was intrigued by the male race – men back then were always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family dealt with this by marrying rich or old ladies—I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to mess with the heads of heiresses."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes searches for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he soaked up inspiration for his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that has been swallowed up by nature.
But it's a special place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I was like, 'Now to get the hell back to real life.'"
