Red meat, dairy, and chocolate can relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to eat meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps create immune cells that support gut resistance.
Study leader Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
As soon as the scales tilt to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, scientists found the presence of immune cells supporting the body's tolerance in the stomach of mice with a particular bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to create cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We found a link between a type of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is a normal part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support the body's tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had."
He also suggested that if the same was shown to be true for humans, then combining L. reuteri with a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory gut environment.
Graduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, studying a certain type of immune cells that promote body tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group of identical mice kept separately lacked cells.
She deduced that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome — a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of the mice were tested by DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
Mice that were bred in a sterile environment and lacked an gut microbiome — so they did not develop this kind of immune cell — were given L. reuteri and developed immune cells.
To understand how the bacterium affects the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid—without the bacterium—to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. At the same time, after halving the doses of tryptophan, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tracts.
It is not known if tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr Cervantes-Barragan added: "All of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control inflammation of the inner surface of the gut.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may increase the cell population."
