White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn for last month's celebration of the U.S. manufacturing industry cost $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a showcase of U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials toured the product parade from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and requested the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn in an "emergency," according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for managing the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy's deputy commander for aviation, the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7 a.m. for the parade, which is scheduled to begin at 3 p.m. and will remain in place until the site is completely cleared, which was scheduled to be cleared between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m.
The email further stated that if there is a delay in departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to working time regulations.
The original crew remained at the scene that evening along with the helicopter, along with a unit of security personnel.
It was not clear from the footage - obtained by TIME - whether a second crew was eventually dispatched.
The Hatch Act prevents civil servants from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this regulation.
"We wondered if this was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured that everything was in order," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked," the deputy commander wrote back.
This "Made in America" show was designated as an official event by the White House and would not be covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
In attending the event, the president pushed for health care reform that was passing the Senate and spoke of trying to rein in government regulations.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after a presidential plane taxied in the background at his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is flooded with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
"The White House is delighted with the 'Made in America' show, which showcased products from all 50 states that Americans make from American materials," said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often practice landing in the Washington area and South Lawn and practice possible arrivals with the President of the United States at the White House with maximum precision.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the crew's current training, a state official said.
On the same day, the helicopter unit flew another eleven hours as part of "non-presidential support missions."
The White House said no other props were paid for with taxpayer money.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company had no involvement in negotiations to build a helicopter at South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the show is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017, while DoD reimbursement for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit's records show a time of 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the helicopter's actual operating costs are well below that amount.
"To state taxpayer costs based on reimbursement estimates is very misleading," Walters said.
"These estimates include staffing, maintenance, and many other hidden costs that are included in annual costs."
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD reimbursements do not include personnel costs, but do include fuel costs, maintenance, and contract costs.
Then-White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for parade purposes.
"The idea behind the show this week is to showcase products made in the U.S.," Spicer said.
"I am aware that Sikorsky and the State of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to the defense of our state, and that they provide jobs for hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, as do most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military facilities that countless American citizens are involved in building.
This fact should be recalled."
It's unclear if Trump also looked at the helicopter on his patrol to South Lawn. All we can say for sure is that he got behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I own three myself."
