In addition to the Pardubice Region, it has already completed all the candidates.
According to his words, he did not interfere with them significantly.
He even agreed to let the Moravian-Silesian one be led by the governor and shadow minister of education of ANO, Ivo Vondrák.
"But if he succeeds, he will have to choose whether he wants to be an MP or a governor," Babiš confirmed his earlier position.
You have angered many representatives and national politicians with your thesis that directly elected mayors should manage municipalities and towns themselves, only with managers.
Are you serious?
It wasn't like that.
I am a supporter of direct democracy, we elect the president directly, and I believe that we should elect mayors in the same way.
In my book, I do not talk about abolishing representatives, they can easily be there.
The question is how many there will be.
During the presentation of your book What I Dream About When I Happen to Sleep, I heard with my own ears that you spoke about the abolition of councils.
I don't remember that.
I spoke about direct elections and a reduction in the number of representatives.
New York, with a population of nine million, has five districts and 51 councils.
Prague with 1.2 million citizens has 1171 representatives.
And the mayor is reproached for not building enough and not preparing large projects, but she does not have the competence to do so.
The same is true of a government that has been led by only two people in our history, Klaus and Zeman.
Which is not to say they did it well.
But the current prime minister does not manage anything, he only moderates the debate.
It can't work that way.
Is that why you want to enforce a majority system?
It would be ideal, but it's hard to enforce.
In the program, we only have a change to a one-round election to the Senate.
We have also proposed a rolling mandate for ministers and an amendment to the Rules of Procedure of the Chamber of Deputies to avoid unnecessary exhibitions of Members who are supposed to work mainly in commissions and committees, rather than showing off at meetings of the House.
It is certainly not true that I want to destroy the parliamentary system.
But that is exactly what your opponents fear.
That as a dictator you will run the government, control the House with 101 deputies, abolish the regions and the Senate, and through grateful mayors and control the whole country.
That is certainly not the case.
There is nothing wrong with debating the number of Members.
French President Macron has announced a reduction in the legislature by a third, while there are 57,000 French people per lawmaker, while in our country it comes to 17,000 Czechs.
But no one accuses Macron of threatening democracy.
Even if someone wins elections in the Czech Republic by a majority, we have mechanisms that would prevent them from making any dramatic changes.
But the temptations for those who have a parliamentary majority are great, just look at Poland or Hungary.
There is no such threat in the case of the ANO movement.
We just need a team that will work for the people in government, not for their parties or departments.
I do not understand, for example, why we have not been able to agree that only the salaries of teachers, employees in culture and social services will increase.
Why did they outvote me and add 21 percent to GIBS officers, who are already taking 60,000?
Is that what you would do as Prime Minister?
The prime minister is supposed to intervene when ministers behave wastefully, confuse the government with a travel agency, and would like to do business with state money like Marian Jurečka, who wanted to buy forests in Romania and land in Africa.
Ministers should not quarrel in the government, they should resolve differences outside it.
Ready-made material must go to the cabinet, there is no room for coalition splits, power votes and deals, where decisions are to be made.
How do you want to have a cohesive team when ministers behave mainly in a partisan way?
Above the parties is a constitutional law.
When it came to breaking bread, Sobotka said that the coalition agreement did not apply and kicked Babis out of the government.
Any prime minister can do that.
But if he is a personality and has managerial skills, he has no need for such empty gestures.
It measures everyone equally and demands perfect performance from everyone.
Do you already know who you would nominate for Minister of Finance?
I don't think about it at all, we probably won't even be in the government, nobody wants to work with us, even though I don't know what I did so terribly.
So much skepticism is misplaced.
The mayors have acquired a businessman named Dědek, who would like to cooperate with you, and the wing of Jiří Čunek, who is favourable to you, may win with the People's Party.
I don't think so.
The ČSSD is led by Lubomír Zaorálek, who does not rule out a coalition with ANO, while Václav Klaus Jr., who will also not be against it, may succeed in the ODS.
I would leave it to the voters.
Deputy Prime Minister and Vice-Chairman of ANO Richard Brabec said that you have many points in common with Tomio Okamura's SPD, for example in the area of the economy.
So the Okamuras come into consideration as a coalition partner?
Mr. Brabec claims that he did not say it that way.
Mr. Okamura has his own political history, he ran as a puppet of Vít Bárta for VV, then he raised money from Úsvit for his company, some kind of coup took place there.
He, of course, is a distinctive personality.
However, somewhat brownish.
If I take his program, he has a broad involvement of people in the management of society, direct democracy, one can agree with that.
I am not asking you that at all.
I wonder whether you find it acceptable to have xenophobic views, who speaks at demonstrations with the gallows and who wants to leave the EU?
We are not considering cooperation with Mr Okamura's party, I cannot imagine it.
Obviously, he went into politics to profit from it.
What about the Communists' tacit support for your minority government?
I can't even imagine that, but the voters will decide.
It will be about negotiating the winner with the second in order, but God knows who will be the winner and who will be the two.
Of course, it is important that they are able to agree on the coalition government's programme.
Let's go back to your efforts to run the state like a business.
But the government simply has to follow it, Prime Minister Sobotka let everything rot, he never decided.
Coalition issues such as CEB or EGAP did not work.
After all, Sobotka is his puppet, and I think that was the reason why he fired me.
As soon as he did so, ČEZ took control of the Czech government.
It is unbelievable that the Prime Minister brought a resolution written by ČEZ's management, which instructs the Minister of Finance how to vote at the ČEZ General Meeting.
If you become Prime Minister, will you change the personnel situation in the Supervisory Board and replace the top management of ČEZ?
Jesus, if I'm going to be prime minister, we'll see.
I'm not one yet.
It is rumored that ČEZ has already sent signals in your direction.
He would like to exchange good cooperation with ČSSD for even better cooperation with ANO.
Maybe after the elections everything will go on again.
I don't know anything about it.
I don't have any lobbyist Pokorný or Růžička, I'm a separate unit and I don't deal with this at all.
So answer directly.
If you become the head of the government, will you seek to replace the leadership of ČEZ, Czech Television or the General Health Insurance Company, i.e. the institutions you criticize?
I would like ČEZ to be a transparent company.
So far, he has been doing what he wanted for years, thanks to commissions for traditional political parties.
It is enough to look up the statements of Mr. Schwarzenberg.
Although the state has a majority in ČEZ, it has never managed it, it was only there in numbers, which is wrong.
For me, this is a trivial matter.
ČEZ is supposed to take Dukovany, value it, put it in a subsidiary, arrange financing, make a supply competition, or find a co-investor and build a new nuclear unit.
The concept that the state should finance and build new nuclear units is absurd.
And Czech Television?
Some of her shows are waging a permanent campaign against me, but I don't have and won't have any authority to fire anyone.
But to dominate, yes.
I don't want to dominate anyone.
I am just saying that citizens pay about EUR 7.2 billion a year for public radio and television, but they do not really know how these institutions run their finances.
How come they don't know?
After all, the Chamber of Deputies approves a report on their financial management, which has a direct impact on the positions of the general directors of Czech Television and Czech Radio.
Look at how the news is discussed, at the super power pact Sobotka Kalousek, which has always worked.
This applies both to the current parliamentary commission on leaks from investigative files and to Lex Babiš.
And Sobotka was so stupid that he let Kalousek push me out of the government, which added a percentage to TOP 09, but the ČSSD took them away.
They are afraid of the disruption of their corrupt system, so they talk about the threat to democracy posed by Babiš.
No one is immune.
What do you say to the articles describing how the first vice-chairman of ANO, Jaroslav Faltýnek, is building a power base by appointing his son to the supervisory board of Teplárny Brno and arranging contracts with municipal and state companies such as the Prague Public Transport Company or Czech Railways for his related lawyer Květoslav Hlína?
We have a permanent dispute on this.
I don't like it and I've reproached him several times.
Faltýnek argues that the lawyer works at significantly lower rates and is reliable.
I wouldn't do that.
As Minister of Finance, I had no one.
Unlike the Socans, we never had a corruption affair, no Pelta, Kratochvílová, Březina.
If there was any hint of clientelism, we immediately fired such a person.
I am uncompromising in this respect.
If something like that happened, we would get rid of anyone, it doesn't matter who it is.
